etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in Gideon Harvey (c1636–?1702), physician. From post-classical Latin raninus from classical Latin rāna frog + -īnus. On the reason for the name in sense A. 1 see quot. 1615

definitions: Designating the deep lingual artery and vein, which run on each side of the undersurface of the tongue from the back to the tip. In early use also: †designating a sublingual salivary gland (obsolete).
Resembling a frog; of the nature of a frog; of, relating to, or characteristic of frogs, specifically (Zoology) those of the subfamily Raninae.
A frog of the subfamily Raninae.
